  "prompt": "Is the Tamil language older than Sanskrit? How old is it when compared to all other languages of the world?",
  "response": "The question of whether Tamil is older than Sanskrit is complex and depends on how one defines \"older.\" Both Tamil and Sanskrit are ancient languages, but they belong to different language families and have different historical contexts.\n\n**Tamil:**\n- Tamil is a Dravidian language and is considered to have a continuous history of over 2,000 years. The earliest Tamil inscriptions date back to around 500 BCE, and the oldest extant literature in Tamil, the Sangam literature, dates from roughly 300 BCE to 300 CE. Tamil is one of the longest-surviving classical languages in the world, with a rich literary tradition that continues to this day.\n\n**Sanskrit:**\n- Sanskrit is an ancient Indo-Aryan language. The Vedic texts, which are some of the oldest Sanskrit texts, date back to around 1500 BCE or earlier. However, the literary tradition of Sanskrit as we recognize it today (Classical Sanskrit) was further developed around the 4th century BCE with the works of poets and playwrights.\n\nIn terms of their origins:\n- The Vedic texts of Sanskrit are generally considered to be older than the earliest Tamil inscriptions. Thus, from a historical perspective, Sanskrit has older roots in terms of written records.\n\nWhen comparing both languages to the timeframe of human languages globally:\n- Language is believed to have emerged in humans tens of thousands of years ago, but most written records are from much later. Languages like Sumerian and Egyptian hieroglyphs (from around 3100 BCE) are among the earliest known written forms. However, spoken languages would have existed far earlier than written records.\n\nIn conclusion:\n- While Sanskrit may have earlier written records, Tamil boasts a remarkable continuity and literary tradition. Both languages are ancient and significant in their own rights within their respective cultural and historical contexts. Tamil is one of the oldest continuously spoken and written languages, while Sanskrit has a pivotal role in the history of Indo-European languages.",
